04033nam a22005415i 9780822383079DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20012001ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223830797 a10.1515/97808223830792doi  a(DE-B1597)551951  a(OCoLC)1055288737  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHQ806b.D67 2001 7aHIS0450002bisacsh1 aDopico Black, Georgina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPerfect Wives, Other Women :bAdultery and Inquisition in Early Modern Spain /cGeorgina Dopico Black. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2001] 4c©2001  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b1 illustration  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface -- tChapter one Visible Signs: Reading the Wife's Body in Early Modern Spain -- tChapter two ''Pasos de un peregrino'': Luis de León Reads the Perfect Wife -- tChapter three The Perfected Wife: Signs of Adultery and the Adultery of Signs in Calderón's El médico de su honra -- tChapter four Sor Juana's Empeños: The Imperfect Wife -- tConclusion: ''Como anillo al dedo'' -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Perfect Wives, Other Women Georgina Dopico Black examines the role played by women's bodies-specifically the bodies of wives-in Spain and Spanish America during the Inquisition. In her quest to show how both the body and soul of the married woman became the site of anxious inquiry, Dopico Black mines a variety of Golden Age texts for instances in which the era's persistent preoccupation with racial, religious, and cultural otherness was reflected in the depiction of women.Subject to the scrutiny of a remarkable array of gazes-inquisitors, theologians, religious reformers, confessors, poets, playwrights, and, not least among them, husbands-the bodies of perfect and imperfect wives elicited diverse readings. Dopico Black reveals how imperialism, the Inquisition, inflation, and economic decline each contributed to a correspondence between the meanings of these human bodies and "other" bodies, such as those of the Jew, the Moor, the Lutheran, the degenerate, and whoever else departed from a recognized norm. The body of the wife, in other words, became associated with categories separate from anatomy, reflecting the particular hermeneutics employed during the Inquisition regarding the surveillance of otherness.Dopico Black's compelling argument will engage students of Spanish and Spanish American history and literature, gender studies, women's studies, social psychology and cultural studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aAdulteryzSpainxHistory. 0aInquisitionzSpainxHistory. 0aWiveszSpainxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Spain & Portugal.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822383079zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822383079423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822383079.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles